<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Federal quarantine restrictions to prevent the further spread of tiny bee mites have been reduced in <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. However, the tiny killer mites _ <LOCATION> Varroa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jacobsoni </LOCATION> _ still remain a potential threat to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bee industry, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday. All or parts of 13 states remain under federal quarantine restrictions. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Glosser </PERSON>, administrator of the department's <ORGANIZATION> Animal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Plant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inspection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, said the revision for <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> retains `` only that portion of each state that must be quarantined to keep the <LOCATION> Varroa </LOCATION> mite from spreading.'' <PERSON> Glosser </PERSON> said the statewide quarantine in <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> was reduced to parts of <PERSON> Adams </PERSON>, <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> and <PERSON> Wilkinson </PERSON> counties, while the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> quarantine area was reduced to part of <LOCATION> Klickitat </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. Varroa mites were discovered in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> last September in a <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> apiary. Since then, they have been found in 12 other states: <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION