n dogs, which he often referred to as his `` babies.'' Strote has estimated the value of the estate at $ 11 million. His manager of 37 years, <PERSON> Seymoour </PERSON> <PERSON> Heller </PERSON>, has estimated the figure at $ 20 million. Strote on Tuesday defended the signing of the new will and two trusts. He said he had <PERSON> Liberace </PERSON> examined by a doctor first, and the doctor was convinced <PERSON> Liberace </PERSON> was `` in good condition and could understand'' the documents. `` I wanted to make sure he was physically able to go through the documents and understand them,'' <PERSON> Strote </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Strote </PERSON> said <PERSON> Liberace </PERSON> signed the will and two trusts, but balked at a fourth document, a living will that would allow doctors to remove life support systems if they became necessary. `` He said ` I just ca n't sign this,''' <PERSON> Strote </PERSON> recalled. <PERSON> Strote </PERSON> said he felt he had to move quickly in tying down the entertainer's assets and cutting expenditures, which he said were running $ 100,000 to $ 200,000 a month, more than the estate was generating. `` I wanted to liquidate the property while his image and likeness were fresh in the minds of the buying public,'' Strote testified. An auction of Liberace memorabilia in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> earlier this month netted some $ 2 million.
