for a taxi in the street outside his home. With him was a woman identified as his sister-in-law. She was unhurt. According to a police spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity in accordance with Greek practice, two armed men emerged from a parked car. One man fired at Agopian, using solid shotgun slugs, the type used in <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> for boar-hunting. <PERSON> Agopian </PERSON>, hit with two slugs in the chest and elbow, tried to flee. The man ran after him and fired two more slugs into his head and chest. The attackers got away in a car left parked across the street from the second-floor apartment where <PERSON> Agopian </PERSON> and his wife lived. The victim was first identified as <PERSON> Abdul </PERSON> <PERSON> Mohammed </PERSON> <PERSON> Kashim </PERSON>, 39, from a South Yemeni diplomatic passport he was carrying. But following reports from <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> saying the dead man was the long-sought leader of <LOCATION> ASALA </LOCATION>, the ministry said his wife revealed his real identity. `` He'd lived in <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION> for at least a year, possibly longer, as <PERSON> Henri </PERSON> <PERSON> Titizian </PERSON>, but he traveled abroad very frequently on the <LOCATION> Yemeni </LOCATION> passport,'' said a police source, who spoke on condition of anonymity. The source said <PERSON> Agopian </PERSON> planned to open a supermarket in <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Agopian </PERSON>, whose name has also been given as <PERSON> Hagop </PERSON> <PERSON> Hagopian </PERSON>, was reported killed in an Israeli air raid on a Palestinian camp near <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> during <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s 1982 summer invasion of <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. But there were also reports that <PERSON> Agopian </PERSON> was still alive and active in the terrorist organization he had founded, and had merely changed identities. Armenian sources in <LOCATION> Athens </LOCATION>, speaking on condition of a