<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Oil prices seesawed and then slumped in a wild trading session driven by speculation about the outcome of a meeting between <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> and independent oil exporters. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the June contract for <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION> crude jumped 12 cents per barrel to $ 18.72 by noon Wednesday but tumbled late in the day and closed at $ 18.27, down 33 cents from the previous close. Similar swings affected refined products traded on the exchange. The near-month contracts for wholesale unleaded gasoline fell .06 cent a gallon to 52.36 cents, and wholesale heating oil fell .27 cent a gallon to 51.77 cents. Traders said the market strengthened in early activity because of indications that the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION> and a group of non-cartel oil exporters, meeting in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>, might agree on 5 percent production cuts aimed at eliminating excess supplies and raising prices. But later rumors hit the market that key <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> member <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> had walked out of the meeting. By another unconfirmed account, the non-OPEC participants at the meeting had inflated their production figures so the 5 percent output reduction proposal would be largely meaningless. Some traders who had bought oil on the hunch that prices would rise because of the meeting became nervous and sold, accelerating the late-afternoon slide. Others said the market closed in a position to rally sharply if the <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> and non-OPEC bargainers can devise a production-cutting pact. Some said prices easily could surge toward $ 19 a barrel.
